steps.description:
While the general stopping power of a pistol is measurably low compared to almost any long gun, you want to make an informed choice to give you the best advantage. Smaller calibers, such as .380, 9mm, etc, generally result in a higher bullet velocity, reduced recoil which allows for fast follow-up shots, higher capacity magazines (or smaller framed guns), and higher velocity bullets. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/ff/Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-4Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-4Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/ff/Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-4Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-4Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Large calibers, such as the venerable .45 feature slower bullets that have increased overall diameter, allowing for a wider initial wound channel (which gives you a slightly increased chance of hitting something vital). The heavier bullets and generally high muzzle energies increase recoil, resulting in slower follow-up shots and the larger diameter of the cartridges means lower capacity magazines. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/f9/Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-4Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-4Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/f9/Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-4Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-4Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

They are magazine fed, which means that after you have depleted anywhere between 5 and 33 rounds (depending on the model of the handgun, the capacity of the magazine, and applicable state/local laws), you can quickly change magazines and get back into the fight. (Note that this only holds true for as many magazines as you have pre-loaded with ammunition. Reloading a magazine under stress with loose rounds can take a painfully long amount of time, or be nearly impossible to complete due to the decreased motor skills caused by the effects of large amounts of adrenaline. ){"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/af/Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-17Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-17Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/af/Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-17Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-17Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

The force required to operate the slide on the firearm makes them much more desirable for multiple-shot encounters as the slide's action dampens the recoil to some degree. This allows for faster and more accurate follow-up shots. The rearward action of the slide as it ejects the spent casing reduces the overall recoil from firing the round due to its action reducing the energy created by accelerating the bullet down the barrel. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/c/cf/Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-17Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-17Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/c/cf/Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-17Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-17Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Pistols are more difficult to operate safely. Clearing the handgun (removing the ammunition to make it "safe") takes more steps and discipline than a revolver. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/4a/Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-18Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-18Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/4a/Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-18Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-18Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

The mechanical operation of pistols is more complex than that of revolvers, creating more opportunities for the failure of one or more components to disable the pistol. As you might imagine, stoppages of this nature in a life-threatening situation can be very problematic. In the case where a cartridge fails to feed properly into the chamber, a pistol is rendered inoperable until the stoppage is cleared, whereas with a revolver, pulling the trigger again when a cartridge fails to fire will rotate the cylinder, bringing a new cartridge into line with the firing pin. This drawback to a pistol requires extra training and practice ensure the steps to clear the stoppage and return the firearm to working order can be performed instinctually. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/88/Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-18Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-18Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/88/Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-18Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-18Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

The multiple moving parts of a pistol means that in general, they are chambered for less powerful calibers than Revolvers. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/a2/Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-18Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-18Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/a2/Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-18Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-18Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Reliability is the most attractive feature of a revolver. A standard shooter would have a hard time making a spurless (hammerless), double-action revolver not shoot when the trigger is pulled. The design is simple, and the use is even simpler: pick up a loaded gun, disengage the safety (if applicable), and pull the trigger, and it will fire. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/57/Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-21Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-21Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/57/Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-21Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-21Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Simpler operation means that a new shooter is more easily able to unload a revolver. Removing all of the ammunition from the cylinder quickly unloads the gun. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/d2/Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-21Bullet2.jpg/v4-459px-Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-21Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/d2/Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-21Bullet2.jpg/v4-759px-Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-21Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":344,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":568.9560439560439,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Revolvers also generally are chambered in more powerful calibers than their semi-automatic counterparts. .357 Magnum and .44 Magnum revolvers are extremely popular and pack a great deal of energy when fired. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/08/Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-21Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-21Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/08/Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-21Bullet3.jpg/v4-759px-Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-21Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":347,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":573.1318681318681,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Reloading a revolver is a very dexterous operation and it may take some time. Even speed loaders require practice and still are not as fast as changing out a preloaded magazine as you can do with a pistol. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/71/Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-22Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-22Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/71/Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-22Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-22Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Cylinders often can not hold nearly as many cartridges as pistol magazines, meaning one must reload more often in the rare event of a prolonged firefight. One should note, however, that most self-defense encounters require less than four or five shots. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/7e/Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-22Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-22Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/7e/Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-22Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-22Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Although they may be more "reliable" they are by no means more rugged. The mechanism for DA revolvers require clockwork precision. As pointed out by renowned firearms trainer Massad Ayoob, auto-pistols are superior in dealing with grit and grime (such as chunks of gore etc. ){"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/3/36/Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-22Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-22Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/3/36/Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-22Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-22Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

The biggest benefit of shotguns is their ability to shoot shot (and just about anything else). The spreading out of the shot when fired allows a larger area to be hit with each trigger pull, reducing the requirement for precision shooting, and, depending on the type of ammunition and range, can cause greater damage than a single bullet from a handgun. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/e3/Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-31Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-31Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/e3/Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-31Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-31Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Some shotguns have the flexibility of shooting shot or bullet-type projectiles (known as "slugs"). This allows them to have the characteristics of rifles but also the option to use shot depending on the situation. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/58/Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-31Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-31Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/58/Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-31Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-31Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Shotguns, like many long guns, are also customizable and versatile. Most modern shotguns can be outfitted with different length barrels, stocks, fore ends, sights and many other accessories to fit your needs. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/3/3c/Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-31Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-31Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/3/3c/Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-31Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-31Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

The use of chokes, a narrowing "funnel"-like section at the end of the barrel, allows you to control how much the shot disperses out of the end of the barrel. Some shotguns have threading or another method at the end of the barrel to allow you to easily change a choke depending on your needs. For defensive use, cylinder bore (or basically no choke at all) and sometimes improved cylinder (IC) chokes are most common. These allow the shot to spread out quickly and increase the chance of hitting your target. However, at longer ranges (greater than 20yds or so) the shot spreads out too much and will not be able to guarantee a good hit. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/7c/Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-31Bullet4.jpg/v4-460px-Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-31Bullet4.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/7c/Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-31Bullet4.jpg/v4-760px-Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-31Bullet4.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Another benefit of shooting shot from a shotgun is the inherent lack of penetration. For home protection, lighter shot will likely become less than lethal once it goes through a wall, protecting innocent family members or neighbors. Typically, the penetration is proportional to the size of the shot (for example, large buckshot is still capable of substantial penetration.) Although the "best" size is a hotly debated topic, smaller bird shot and skeet/clay target sized shot at close range can be very effective. Shotgun barrels range in length from 18.5 inch (47.0 cm) "home defense" barrels to 24 inch (61.0 cm) hunting barrels. Also, many shotguns are made so the barrel can be changed easily. This way, you can put a short barrel on for home defense, and a long barrel for hunting or busting clays. Don't forget to practice with your short barrel, though. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/9/97/Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-31Bullet6.jpg/v4-460px-Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-31Bullet6.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/9/97/Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-31Bullet6.jpg/v4-760px-Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-31Bullet6.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Although a shotgun firing shot will produce a spread much larger than a solid projectile, it does not preclude the need to aim. At normal household room distances, the shot spread, even with no choke, is barely the size of a softball. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/25/Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-32Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-32Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/25/Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-32Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-32Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Unless you are using slugs, shotguns are useless at longer ranges. Between the spreading of the shot, and the light weight of the pellets, the power of the weapon drops off precipitously as range increases. That said, most self defense encounters happen well within range of a shotgun. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/72/Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-32Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-32Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/72/Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-32Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-32Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Shotguns with heavy loads, such as 00 buck, can kick pretty hard, making them potentially difficult to control without practice. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/e6/Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-32Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-32Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/e6/Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-32Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-32Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Unlike pistol bullets, which typically create narrow permanent wound channels, the greatly increased speed of rifle bullets create a shock wave that can permanently destroy large amounts of tissue, greatly increasing your chances of stopping the threat with a single reasonably placed shot. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/be/Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-35Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-35Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/be/Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-35Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-35Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Rifle cartridges are far more powerful than handgun cartridges. This greater power means you can shoot effectively at a much longer distance. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/c/ca/Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-35Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-35Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/c/ca/Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-35Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-35Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Rifles still require a good deal of precision, but the dexterity needed for a pistol is not necessary, and stopping power is much improved. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/00/Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-35Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-35Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/00/Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-35Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-35Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

As with any long gun, maneuverability is greatly reduced due to its overall length. Home defense situations may require you to place the stock below your shoulder, reducing your accuracy. Movement around corners and through doors may be hampered by your barrel preceding you through the door, warning an enemy that you're there. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/08/Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-36Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-36Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/08/Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-36Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-36Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":346,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":571.0439560439561,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Rifles are also more capable of "over penetration". This is where the bullet passes through an object, such as a wall, or your intended target and continue on with enough force to injure or kill. Over penetration can be mitigated through proper ammunition choice, but is always a serious consideration with rifles. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/84/Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-36Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-36Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/84/Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-36Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-36Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Rifle ammunition is much more expensive than handgun ammunition. This can mean that it is more expensive to practice with your rifle, and reduce the amount of training and practice you can afford. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/bf/Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-36Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-36Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/bf/Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-36Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-36Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

The overall length of rifles also means that they are slower to aim than a handgun due to their weight. Compared to a pistol, swinging a rifle around to engage a threat can take longer, and in a self defense situation, lost time can be deadly. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/af/Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-36Bullet4.jpg/v4-460px-Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-36Bullet4.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/af/Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-36Bullet4.jpg/v4-760px-Choose-a-Firearm-for-Personal-or-Home-Defense-Step-36Bullet4.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
